'''AIDS.gov''' is an internet portal for all Federal domestic [[HIV]] and AIDS resources and information.  On [[World AIDS Day]], December 1, 2006, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services launched AIDS.gov. The site contains content and links that guide users to their desired information.<ref>[http://www.hhs.gov/news/press/2006pres/20061130.html Mike Leavitt, Secretary of Health and Human Services, World AIDS Day 2006 Press Release]</ref><ref>[http://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2006/12/20061201-2.html White House World AIDS Day 2006]</ref>

AIDS.gov is intended as a resource for the general public, federal staff/agencies, state staff, federal grantees, medical and research institutions, and other HIV and AIDS-related organizations. It is sponsored by the Department of Health and Human Services’ (HHS) Office of Public Health and Science and Office of the Assistant Secretary for Public Affairs and works across the government. 

The content, design and development team includes representatives from HHS and other government agencies working on AIDS domestically.

== Awards ==

On March 11, 2008, AIDS.gov received the American Association of Webmasters Gold Award. This is a peer-reviewed, criteria-based award for achievement in web design in which rigorous standards of HTML code, web design, technical achievement, and overall content are evaluated.

In August 2010, the AIDS.gov blog was selected as a top government blog on Juggle.com.<ref>[http://www.juggle.com/blog-aids-gov-top-government-blog Juggle Top Government Blog Award to AIDS.gov]</ref>

== Media ==

In January, 2008, AIDS.gov started a [http://Blog.AIDS.gov blog] on how to use new media tools in response to HIV/AIDS. The blog has since expanded to cover HIV policy and research, as well as new media. AIDS.gov is also engaged in other new media activities <ref>[http://www.dhhs.gov/news/press/2008pres/05/20080507b.html Department of Health and Human Services "AIDS.gov Goes 2.0" Press Release]</ref>-- from maintaining a presence on social media sites such as Twitter and YouTube to promoting a text messaging campaign with the Kaiser Family Foundation and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.<ref>[http://www.kff.org/hivaids/phip113007nr.cfm HHS and Kaiser Family Foundation Team Up to Promote Text Messaging in the Fight Against HIV/AIDS]</ref> Mobile phone users can text their ZIP code to KNOWIT (566948) and will receive the location of their nearest HIV testing center.<ref>[http://www.aids.gov/knowit.html KNOWIT Campaign]</ref>   

In recognition of the 20th World AIDS Day on December 1, 2008, AIDS.gov took part in several key new media activities:<ref>[http://www.prweekus.com/World-AIDS-Day-efforts-utilize-youth-new-media/article/121540/ PRWeek World AIDS Day 2008 Article]</ref><ref>[http://blog.ogilvypr.com/?p=509 Ogilvy Blog Post: World AIDS Day 2008: AIDS.gov Celebrates Two Years]</ref> the Facing AIDS initiative,<ref>[http://www.aids.gov/world_aids_day.html AIDS.gov World AIDS Day 2008 Page]</ref> Bloggers Unite for World AIDS Day,<ref>[http://unite.blogcatalog.com/ Bloggers Unite]</ref> and Second Life<ref>[http://www.karunasl.info/WorldAIDSDaySL/?p=7 Second Life World AIDS Day 2008]</ref> World AIDS Day events.<ref>[http://www.hhs.gov/ophs/news/20081126.html Department of Health and Human Services World AIDS Day 2008 Press Release]</ref>

In recognition of World AIDS Day on December 1, 2009, AIDS.gov again hosted the Facing AIDS initiative, among other activities. Facing AIDS encouraged people around the country (and world) to take a photo of themselves saying why they were "Facing AIDS" for World AIDS Day and to upload the photo to the Facing AIDS group on Flickr. Over 850 photos were submitted to the Facing AIDS group, and Flickr featured the initiative on its blog.<ref>[http://blog.flickr.net/en/2009/12/01/facing-aids/ Facing AIDS 2009 Flickr Blog Post]</ref>

For National HIV Testing Day (NHTD) 2009, June 27, AIDS.gov shared testing messages from President Obama,<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/gettested/ White House National HIV Testing Day 2009 Blog Post]</ref> and HHS Secretary Sebelius and DC Mayor Fenty.<ref>[http://www.aids.gov/nhtd2009.html HHS Secretary Sebelius and DC Mayor Fenty HIV Testing PSA]</ref> As part of NHTD 2009, AIDS.gov produced the “''I Know. I Took the Test''” blog series that highlighted campaigns focused on sharing personal HIV testing stories from organizations such as [http://blog.aids.gov/2009/06/i-know-i-took-the-test-stories-from-the-positive-project.html The Positive Project], [http://www.livingquilt.org/ Southern AIDS Living Quilt], [http://www.napwa.org/ National Association of People with AIDS], and [http://www.poz.com/ POZ].  In addition, in collaboration with the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]], AIDS.gov developed and promoted an accompanying widget with videos from the campaigns, and with the President's NHTD message.<ref>[http://www.aids.gov/national_hiv_testing_day/index.html AIDS.gov National HIV Testing Day 2009 Page]</ref>

For National HIV Testing Day (NHTD) on June 27, 2010, AIDS.gov worked with [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|HUD's]] Housing Opportunities for Persons with AIDS Program, [[SAMSHA|SAMHSA's]] Center for Mental Health Services, the [[HRSA|Health Resources and Services Administration]] (HRSA), the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]], and others to develop the [http://aids.gov/locator/ HIV/AIDS Prevention & Service Provider Locator]. By entering a location (ZIP code, city and state), an individual can locate nearby prevention, housing, mental health, substance abuse, testing, and treatment services. The locator is a widget that allows organizations and individuals to share the locator on their own blog or website.

